Computes and persists the CACT content-hash tree used to detect stale summaries: builds a per-directory hash node (`f:`/`d:` prefixed children entries) from source file bytes, aggregates deepest-first up to root, and diffs against stored sidecars to determine what needs regenerating.

Freshness is entirely hash-based, never git-derived — this is deliberate (see module doc) so gitignore-invisible edits and uncommitted changes are still caught. Each directory's sidecar lives at `.context/<dir>/hashes.json` (path built by `sidecar`); `cpath::context_dir_of` and `cpath::ancestor_dirs` define the mirrored `.context` layout and must stay in sync with how `ctx-summarize` writes leaves/rollups.

Key entry points: `compute(base, files) -> Result<TreeState, ScanError>` reads every file's bytes and builds the full tree (errors as `ScanError::Io` with path/detail). `load_stored`/`store` round-trip `TreeState` through JSON sidecars; a missing or corrupt sidecar reads as "absent" rather than erroring, which `diff` then treats as stale (via `old.is_none_or(...)`). `diff(current, stored) -> Staleness` returns `stale_dirs` (sorted deepest-first so children regenerate before parents), `changed_files`, and `orphan_leaves` (leaf `.ctx` files for source files that disappeared). `record_missing_artifacts` is a separate pass catching the case where hashes match but the `.ctx` file was simply never written or was deleted — hash diffing alone can't see this gap (referenced internally as "audit finding #11").

Invariant: `aggregate` must be called with a `BTreeMap` containing every ancestor directory in `all`, or intermediate dirs silently get `DirNode::default()` (empty children, hash of empty string) instead of real content — `compute` guarantees this via `cpath::ancestor_dirs`.